<ref>{{cite web |title=The Biographical Dictionary of the Australian Senate 1968 |url=http://biography.senate.gov.au/?search-class=DB_CustomSearch_Widget-db_customsearch_widget&widget_number=3&cs-dates-0=1968&search=Search |publisher=[[Parliament of Australia]] |access-date=21 March 2017}}</ref> Half of its members were elected at the [[1964 Australian Senate election|5 December 1964 half Senate election]] and had terms due to finish on 30 June 1971; the other half were elected at [[1967 Australian Senate election|25 November 1967 half Senate election]] and had terms due to finish on 30 June 1974. The process for filling casual vacancies was complex. While senators were elected for a six-year term, people appointed to a casual vacancy only held office until the earlier of the next election for the House of Representatives or the Senate.<ref name=\"Evans vacancy\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! '''Senator'''\n! colspan=2 | '''Party'''\n! '''State'''\n! '''End term'''\n! '''Years in Office'''\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Ken|Anderson|Ken Anderson (Australian politician)}} || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || [[New South Wales]] || 1971 || 1953\u20131975\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Reg|Bishop}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || [[South Australia]] || 1974 || 1961\u20131981\n|-\n|| [[George Branson]] || {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp; || [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] || [[Western Australia]] || 1971 || 1958\u20131971\n|-\n|| {{sortname|Bill|Brown|Bill Brown (Australian politician)}} {{efn|name=Cohen}} || {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp; || [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] || [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] || 1970 {{efn|name=Appointment|Appointed to a casual vacancy and only held office until the earlier of the next election for the House of Representatives or the Senate.<ref name=\"Evans vacancy\">{{cite web |author=Evans, H |author-link1=Harry Evans (